==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Statue
<hw>Stat"ue</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧ch"⟦oomac⟧; also, st⟦acr⟧t"⟦usl⟧;
135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>statua</ets> (akin to
<ets>stativus</ets> standing still), fr. <ets>stare</ets>,
<ets>statum</ets>, to stand. See <er>Stand</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The likeness of a living being sculptured or modeled in some solid
substance, as marble, bronze, or wax; an image; <as>as, a
<ex>statue</ex> of Hercules, or of a lion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will raise her <qex>statue</qex> in pure gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A portrait.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Statue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Statue
<hw>Stat"ue</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Statued</conjf> <pr>(-⟦usl⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Statuing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To place, as a statue; to form a
statue of; to make into a statue.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The whole man becomes as
if <xex>statued</xex> into stone and earth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Feltham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Statued</ent>⟦br⟧
